{
  "The ISS orbits Earth at an altitude of approximately:": "",
  "35,786 km (geostationary orbit)": "",
  "1,000 km": "",
  "100 km": "",
  "About 400 km in low Earth orbit (LEO)": "",
  "The ISS orbits at approximately 400 km above Earth's surface in low Earth orbit (LEO), which is high enough to experience microgravity but close enough for regular crew and cargo resupply missions. This altitude requires periodic reboosts because atmospheric drag slowly lowers the station's orbit over time.": "",
  "The ISS has been continuously occupied by humans since:": "",
  "1998, particu": "",
  "November 2, 2000": "",
  "1990, particu": "",
  "2010, particu": "",
  "The first permanent crew (Expedition 1) arrived at the ISS on November 2, 2000, and the station has been continuously inhabited ever since, making it over two decades of uninterrupted human presence in space. This record of continuous occupation is the longest in the history of spaceflight.": "",
  "Which five space agencies operate the International Space Station?": "",
  "Only NASA and ESA": "",
  "Only the United States and Russia": "",
  "Only NASA": "",
  "NASA, Roscosmos, ESA, JAXA, and CSA": "",
  "The ISS is a multinational collaborative project involving five space agencies: NASA (United States), Roscosmos (Russia), ESA (European Space Agency), JAXA (Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency), and CSA (Canadian Space Agency). This international partnership represents one of the most complex and cooperative engineering endeavors in human history.": "",
  "How long does it take the ISS to complete one orbit around Earth?": "",
  "12 hours": "",
  "About 92 minutes": "",
  "24 hours": "",
  "1 week": "",
  "The ISS completes one full orbit of Earth approximately every 92 minutes, which means the crew experiences about 16 sunrises and 16 sunsets every 24 hours. This rapid day-night cycle is one reason astronauts use artificial lighting schedules and window covers to maintain a normal sleep-wake routine.": "",
  "How many scientific experiments have been conducted aboard the ISS?": "",
  "Over 3,000": "",
  "About 50": "",
  "About 10": "",
  "About 100": "",
  "The ISS has hosted over 3,000 scientific experiments from researchers in more than 100 countries, making it one of the most productive research laboratories in history. These experiments span fields including biology, physics, materials science, Earth observation, and human physiology, taking advantage of the unique microgravity environment.": "",
  "The ISS solar array span is approximately how wide?": "",
  "About 109 meters, roughly the size of a football field": "",
  "50 meters, particularly regarding span in": "",
  "10 meters, particularly regarding from": "",
  "500 meters, particularly regarding array": "",
  "The ISS measures approximately 109 meters from the tip of one solar array wing to the other, making it roughly the size of an American football field including the end zones. Its large size and reflective solar panels make it easily visible to the naked eye from Earth's surface as a bright, steadily moving point of light.": "",
  "How long do ISS crew members typically stay aboard the station?": "",
  "1 month": "",
  "2 years": "",
  "About 6 months": "",
  "Standard ISS expedition rotations last approximately six months, which provides enough time for crew members to conduct meaningful research while limiting the cumulative health effects of microgravity. Some astronauts have stayed for extended missions of up to a year to study the long-term effects of spaceflight on the human body.": "",
  "The ISS travels through space at approximately what speed?": "",
  "1,000 km/h": "",
  "100 km/h": "",
  "The speed of light": "",
  "About 28,000 km/h (7.66 km/s)": "",
  "The ISS travels at approximately 28,000 km/h (about 7.66 km/s), which is the orbital velocity required to maintain a stable orbit at its altitude of roughly 400 km. At this speed, the station covers a distance equivalent to a trip from Earth to the Moon in about a day.": "",
  "The ISS recycles approximately what percentage of its water?": "",
  "100%": "",
  "About 90%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "10%": "",
  "The ISS's Water Recovery System recycles approximately 90% of all water on board, including moisture from cabin humidity, sweat, and even urine, converting it into clean drinking water. This high recycling efficiency is critical for reducing the amount of water that must be launched from Earth on costly resupply missions.": "",
  "Which spacecraft are used by NASA's Commercial Crew Program to transport astronauts to the ISS?": "",
  "Only the Space Shuttle": "",
  "Only Chinese Shenzhou spacecraft": "",
  "Only the Russian Soyuz": "",
  "SpaceX Crew Dragon and Boeing Starliner": "",
  "NASA's Commercial Crew Program contracts with two private companies to provide crew transportation to the ISS: SpaceX (Crew Dragon) and Boeing (Starliner). This public-private partnership model reduces costs and increases launch frequency compared to government-only programs, while maintaining NASA safety standards.": "",
  "What is Canadarm2?": "",
  "A weapons system for defending the ISS from space debris": "",
  "A communication antenna for contacting Canadian ground stations": "",
  "A robotic arm built by the Canadian Space Agency used for station maintenance, capturing visiting cargo vehicles, and supporting spacewalks": "",
  "A backup solar panel array provided by Canada": "",
  "Canadarm2 is a 17.6-meter-long robotic arm built by the Canadian Space Agency (CSA) that serves as one of the most versatile tools on the ISS. It can move along the station's exterior on a mobile base, grapple visiting cargo spacecraft, assist astronauts during spacewalks, and perform maintenance tasks that would otherwise require risky EVAs.": "",
  "What does LEO stand for in the context of the ISS's orbit?": "",
  "Long Exposure Operation, particularly regarding earth when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "Low Earth Orbit, the region of space within about 2,000 km of Earth's surface where the ISS and many satellites operate": "",
  "Lunar Exploration Orbit, particularly regarding missions following the established framework": "",
  "Light Emission Output, particularly regarding environment based on established principles": "",
  "LEO stands for Low Earth Orbit, which is defined as the region of space from about 160 km to 2,000 km above Earth's surface. The ISS orbits within LEO at about 400 km altitude, which offers the advantage of being relatively accessible for crew launches and resupply missions while still providing a microgravity environment for research.": "",
  "What is an EVA (Extra-Vehicular Activity) in the context of ISS operations?": "",
  "An emergency evacuation procedure used when the station loses pressure": "",
  "A spacewalk in which astronauts exit the station in spacesuits to perform maintenance, repairs, or equipment installation on the station's exterior": "",
  "An automated system that controls the station's external instruments": "",
  "An external video analysis of the station performed by cameras on visiting spacecraft": "",
  "An EVA, commonly called a spacewalk, is any activity where astronauts leave the pressurized environment of the ISS and work outside in the vacuum of space wearing pressurized spacesuits. EVAs are performed for essential tasks such as repairing equipment, installing new modules or experiments, and upgrading station systems, and they typically last 6 to 7 hours.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'microgravity research' as conducted on the ISS?": "",
  "Research that can only be done with very small (micro-sized) equipment under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Scientific experiments performed in the near-weightless environment of orbit, where gravity's effects are minimized, allowing researchers to study phenomena impossible to observe on Earth": "",
  "The study of microscopic organisms found in space, particularly regarding what according to conventional analysis": "",
  "Research into making gravity weaker on Earth's surface, particularly regarding enables under normal circumstances": "",
  "Microgravity research takes advantage of the near-weightless conditions aboard the ISS to study physical, chemical, and biological processes without the masking effects of gravity. This enables discoveries in areas such as crystal growth (producing larger and purer crystals), fluid physics, combustion science, and human physiology that are impossible to replicate in ground-based laboratories.": "",
  "What does the term 'expedition' mean in ISS operations?": "",
  "A cargo resupply mission that delivers food and equipment to the station": "",
  "A single spacewalk performed by an astronaut outside the station": "",
  "A journey to another planet launched from the ISS": "",
  "A numbered crew rotation period, typically lasting about six months, during which a designated crew lives and works aboard the ISS": "",
  "In ISS terminology, an 'expedition' refers to a numbered crew increment during which a team of typically six astronauts lives and works aboard the station for approximately six months. Expedition 1 began in November 2000, and each subsequent expedition number represents the next crew rotation cycle.": "",
  "What is orbital decay in the context of the ISS?": "",
  "The ISS slowly falling apart due to age and wear": "",
  "The process of the ISS moving farther from Earth over time": "",
  "The gradual decrease in the ISS's orbital altitude caused by drag from the thin upper atmosphere, requiring periodic reboost maneuvers": "",
  "Radioactive decay of materials used in the station's construction": "",
  "Even at 400 km altitude, trace amounts of atmosphere create drag on the ISS, gradually slowing it and causing it to lose altitude over time. To counteract this orbital decay, the station must be periodically reboosted using thrusters on visiting spacecraft such as the Russian Progress cargo vehicles, raising its orbit back to the desired altitude.": "",
  "What is the definition of a pressurized module on the ISS?": "",
  "A sealed, habitable section of the station maintained at Earth-like atmospheric pressure where crew members can live and work without spacesuits": "",
  "A high-pressure chamber used for medical treatments": "",
  "A module that stores compressed gas tanks for rocket fuel": "",
  "Any external component of the station exposed to the vacuum of space": "",
  "A pressurized module is a habitable compartment on the ISS that is sealed and maintained at approximately one atmosphere of pressure with a breathable air mixture, allowing crew members to live and work in a shirt-sleeve environment. The ISS has about 16 pressurized modules contributed by different partner agencies, including laboratories, living quarters, and connecting nodes.": "",
  "What does 'deorbit' mean as it relates to the ISS's planned end of life?": "",
  "The controlled process of lowering the station's orbit so it reenters Earth's atmosphere and breaks apart, with debris falling into a remote ocean area": "",
  "Disassembling the station piece by piece and returning each module to Earth": "",
  "Launching the station toward the Sun for complete destruction": "",
  "Moving the ISS to a higher orbit where it will remain permanently": "",
  "Deorbiting the ISS involves using a dedicated spacecraft to perform a series of controlled engine burns that lower the station's orbit until it reenters Earth's atmosphere, where most of it will burn up from aerodynamic heating. Any surviving debris is targeted to fall into a remote area of the South Pacific Ocean, and the ISS is currently planned for deorbit around 2031.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'space debris' in the context of ISS safety?": "",
  "Dust from the Moon that drifts into Earth orbit": "",
  "Human-made orbital junk such as defunct satellites, spent rocket stages, and fragments from collisions that pose collision risks to the ISS": "",
  "Natural asteroids that occasionally pass near Earth": "",
  "Trash bags that astronauts throw out of the ISS airlock": "",
  "Space debris consists of human-made objects orbiting Earth that no longer serve a useful purpose, including defunct satellites, spent rocket stages, and thousands of fragments produced by collisions and explosions. Even small pieces of debris pose a serious threat to the ISS because at orbital velocities of 28,000 km/h, a paint chip can damage a window and a centimeter-sized fragment can penetrate the station's hull.": "",
  "What does 'international cooperation' mean in the context of the ISS program?": "",
  "One nation builds and controls the entire station while others watch": "",
  "Nations compete to see who can build the best space station": "",
  "Multiple nations contribute modules, crew, funding, and expertise to jointly build, operate, and benefit from a shared orbital facility": "",
  "An agreement that only allows astronauts from the United Nations to visit the station": "",
  "International cooperation on the ISS means that multiple nations pool their resources, expertise, and funding to jointly construct, operate, and benefit from the station, with each partner contributing specific modules and capabilities. This model has demonstrated that even nations with geopolitical tensions can collaborate productively on complex scientific and engineering projects in space.": "",
  "A ground controller at NASA's Mission Control Center in Houston notices that the ISS has dropped 2 km in altitude over the past month. A cargo spacecraft is currently docked to the station. What routine procedure should be performed to address this?": "",
  "Nothing, because the ISS will naturally return to its original altitude": "",
  "A reboost maneuver should be performed using the docked spacecraft's thrusters to raise the station's orbit back to the desired altitude": "",
  "The crew should perform an EVA to push the station higher": "",
  "The solar panels should be retracted to reduce atmospheric drag permanently": "",
  "The ISS regularly loses altitude due to atmospheric drag, even at 400 km where trace amounts of atmosphere exist. Periodic reboost maneuvers using thrusters on docked Russian Progress cargo vehicles or other visiting spacecraft fire engines to increase the station's velocity and raise its orbit, a routine maintenance procedure performed multiple times per year.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical researcher wants to grow protein crystals in microgravity because previous ISS experiments produced crystals with far fewer defects than those grown on Earth. Why does the microgravity environment produce better crystals?": "",
  "Crystals grow faster in space due to the extreme cold temperatures": "",
  "Without gravity-driven convection and sedimentation, molecules attach to growing crystals more uniformly, producing larger and more ordered structures": "",
  "Space radiation alters the molecular structure of proteins in beneficial ways": "",
  "The vacuum of space removes all impurities from the crystal solution": "",
  "On Earth, gravity causes convection currents and sedimentation in crystal-growing solutions, creating disturbances that introduce defects into the crystal lattice. In the microgravity environment of the ISS, these gravity-driven effects are virtually eliminated, allowing molecules to diffuse slowly and attach to the growing crystal in a more orderly fashion, resulting in larger, higher-quality crystals that are invaluable for drug design research.": "",
  "A space debris tracking team alerts the ISS crew that a fragment from a defunct satellite will pass within 500 meters of the station in 12 hours. What protocol is the crew likely to follow?": "",
  "Immediately abandon the station using escape pods, particularly regarding first when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "If time permits, perform a Debris Avoidance Maneuver (DAM) to adjust the station's orbit; if not, the crew shelters in their docked Crew Dragon or Soyuz spacecraft as a precaution": "",
  "Ignore the warning because the station's shielding can withstand any impact as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "Use Canadarm2 to catch the debris as it passes by, particularly regarding slightly as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "When debris is tracked and a potential close approach is predicted, mission controllers first assess whether there is enough time and tracking data to perform a Debris Avoidance Maneuver, which uses thrusters to slightly adjust the station's orbit. If there is not enough lead time or the tracking data is uncertain, the crew follows a 'shelter in place' protocol by closing hatches and moving into their docked crew vehicles, which could serve as lifeboats if the station were struck.": "",
  "An engineering team is planning the transition from the ISS to commercial space stations. The ISS is scheduled for deorbit around 2031. A project manager asks why commercial stations like those from Axiom Space are being developed before the ISS is retired. What is the strategic reasoning?": "",
  "Commercial stations are being built to serve as luxury hotels and have no research purpose": "",
  "The commercial stations are being launched only because the ISS broke down unexpectedly": "",
  "To ensure continuity of human presence and research capability in low Earth orbit by having commercial platforms operational before the ISS is deorbited": "",
  "NASA wants to sell the ISS to a private company before deorbiting it": "",
  "NASA's strategy is to ensure there is no gap in human presence and research capability in low Earth orbit by supporting commercial space station development while the ISS is still operational. Companies like Axiom Space plan to attach modules to the ISS initially, then detach them to form independent stations, ensuring a smooth transition that preserves decades of LEO research infrastructure and expertise.": "",
  "A life support systems engineer on the ISS notices the water recycling system is processing less water than expected. She determines that the system is recovering only 85% instead of the usual 90%. If the ISS crew of six people each needs about 3 liters of drinking water per day, how significant is this 5% drop, and why does water recycling matter so much?": "",
  "It is insignificant because the ISS can simply request extra water from Earth anytime": "",
  "Every percentage point of recovery matters because launching water from Earth costs thousands of dollars per kilogram, and reduced efficiency means more frequent and expensive resupply missions": "",
  "It does not matter because astronauts can survive on less water in microgravity": "",
  "The crew should simply drink less water until the system is fixed": "",
  "Water recycling efficiency is critical aboard the ISS because launching even 1 kilogram of water from Earth to orbit costs thousands of dollars. A 5% drop in recovery rate means significantly more water must be supplied by cargo missions, impacting both mission budgets and logistics. This is why the Water Recovery System is one of the most important and carefully maintained pieces of equipment on the station.": "",
  "A student watching the ISS pass overhead on a clear evening notices it appears as a bright, steady light moving smoothly across the sky, unlike the blinking lights of airplanes. Why does the ISS appear this way?": "",
  "The light is an optical illusion caused by atmospheric refraction": "",
  "The ISS is actually glowing due to nuclear reactors on board": "",
  "The ISS reflects sunlight off its large solar arrays and white surfaces, and because it is in space there are no navigation lights or blinking beacons": "",
  "The ISS has powerful spotlights that shine down toward Earth": "",
  "The ISS appears as a bright, steady dot moving across the sky because it reflects sunlight off its enormous solar panels and white thermal surfaces, similar to how the Moon shines by reflected sunlight. Unlike aircraft, it has no blinking navigation lights, so its appearance is a smooth, unwavering point of light that traverses the sky in a few minutes due to its orbital speed of 28,000 km/h.": "",
  "A Japanese researcher aboard the ISS is conducting a combustion experiment in the station's microgravity laboratory and observes that flames form perfect spheres instead of the teardrop shape seen on Earth. What causes this difference, and why is this observation scientifically valuable?": "",
  "The spherical shape is caused by the station's rotation creating centrifugal force around the flame": "",
  "Without gravity-driven convection, oxygen reaches the flame equally from all directions, revealing the fundamental physics of combustion without the distorting effects of buoyancy": "",
  "Fire behaves identically in space and on Earth, so the observation must be an error": "",
  "The flame shape is an illusion caused by the special glass in the ISS windows": "",
  "On Earth, gravity creates convection currents that draw hot gas upward and pull fresh oxygen in from below, producing the familiar teardrop flame shape. In microgravity, there is no buoyancy-driven convection, so oxygen diffuses equally from all directions, creating a spherical flame that burns more slowly and at lower temperatures. Studying these simplified flames helps scientists understand fundamental combustion physics, which can lead to improvements in fuel efficiency and fire safety on Earth.": "",
  "A Canadian Space Agency engineer is operating Canadarm2 to capture an approaching cargo spacecraft carrying critical supplies. The arm's operator must grapple the free-flying vehicle and berth it to a docking port. Why is this robotic operation preferred over having the cargo vehicle dock automatically in some cases?": "",
  "Robotic capture is cheaper because it does not require any fuel": "",
  "Using the robotic arm is required by international law for all visiting vehicles": "",
  "Automated docking has never been successfully demonstrated in space": "",
  "Some cargo vehicles lack autonomous docking capability, so the robotic arm captures them at a safe distance and carefully berths them, giving the crew precise control over the approach": "",
  "Vehicles like the original SpaceX Dragon cargo capsule and Northrop Grumman's Cygnus are designed to approach the ISS and then be grappled by Canadarm2 at a safe standoff distance, rather than flying directly into a docking port. This robotic capture method gives the crew and ground controllers precise control over the final berthing process, adding an extra layer of safety compared to fully autonomous docking for vehicles not equipped with that capability.": "",
  "A crew member on the ISS reports feeling disoriented and nauseous during her first week in orbit, and she has difficulty determining which direction is 'up.' Mission control suggests this is normal. What ISS environmental factor contributes to this experience, and how do astronauts adapt?": "",
  "The rapid day-night cycle of 16 sunrises per day causes permanent vertigo in all crew members": "",
  "The symptom indicates a serious medical condition that requires immediate evacuation to Earth": "",
  "In microgravity there is no gravitational 'up' or 'down,' which confuses the vestibular system; most astronauts adapt within 2-3 days as their brain learns to rely more on visual cues": "",
  "The ISS air supply contains trace chemicals that cause nausea in all new arrivals permanently": "",
  "Space adaptation syndrome affects the majority of astronauts during their first few days in microgravity because the vestibular system in the inner ear, which relies on gravity to sense orientation, sends confusing signals when there is no consistent 'down.' The ISS uses color-coded walls and consistent orientation cues to help crew members, and most astronauts fully adapt within 2-3 days as their brains learn to prioritize visual information over vestibular signals.": "",
  "An international relations analyst studying the ISS program notes that during periods of geopolitical tension between the United States and Russia, crew members from both nations continued living and working together aboard the station without interruption. What does this demonstrate about the ISS model of cooperation, and why is it relevant for future space exploration?": "",
  "It only happened because a treaty legally forces continued cooperation regardless of circumstances": "",
  "It demonstrates nothing because astronauts are isolated from political events and unaware of tensions on Earth": "",
  "It shows that shared scientific goals and mutual dependency in space can sustain productive collaboration even when terrestrial political relations are strained, providing a model for future international deep-space missions": "",
  "It proves that political tensions have no effect on any international programs": "",
  "The ISS has proven that international cooperation in space can endure even during periods of significant political tension on Earth, as American and Russian crew members have continued to rely on each other for safety and mission success throughout various geopolitical crises. This model demonstrates that shared scientific objectives and mutual dependency can transcend political divisions, which is an important lesson for planning future international deep-space missions to the Moon and Mars that will require even greater levels of multinational cooperation.": ""
}